Case: Dewayne-Ward-MVA-8-29-2023. Client: Dewayne Ward.

On July 28, 2025, at 10:17:14 AM Eastern Time, a forward of an email in the matter titled Willaims, Ward & Moore v. Robinson was sent by W. Bryce Koon, Esq., of The Whaley Law Firm. The recipient list included Ashlee Williams MVA 8/29/23 - Filevine Project Email Address, Dewayne Ward MVA 8/29/2023 - Filevine Project Email Address, and Julmonzhae Moore MVA 8/29/2023 - Filevine Project Email Address. The forwarded message carried the subject Willaims, Ward & Moore v. Robinson and carried the main body stating: “Good morning counsel, Attached please find Plaintiffs' Discovery Responses. Below you will find a Dropbox link to the document production in this regard.” The Dropbox link provided was: https://www.dropbox.com/scl/fo/f27jsukejdzuxesqz496o/AOngUDwjYgN8Y2nRHEIpqrU?rlkey=fje64jsp5o4uw5m4tasky5vw7&st=q3oemih1&dl=0. The message concluded with thanks from “W. Bryce Koon, Esq.” of The Whaley Law Firm, located at 712 Lyndon Lane, Louisville, KY 40222, with phone number (502) 365-5043 and fax number (502) 237-3207. A confidentiality notice followed, stating that the electronic message is intended only for the named recipient and may contain attorney-client privileged or protected information; if received in error, the recipient should contact The Whaley Law Firm, avoid waiving privilege, and should not use or forward the information. The notice reiterated that if the recipient is not the intended recipient, they should not forward or disclose the content.

The forwarded thread also included an earlier message from July 15, 2025, at 10:44 AM, sent by Zachary Reichle, Associate at Stoll Keenon Ogden PLLC, to counsel. In that message, Reichle asked good morning and followed up on the status of Plaintiffs’ responses to Defendant’s discovery requests. He noted that the records indicated the responses were originally due July 9, but no responses had been received and no extensions of time had been requested. Reichle provided his contact details: zachary.reichle@skofirm.com, direct line 317.224.2473, and the firm’s address at 334 N Senate Ave, Indianapolis, IN 46204, with the firm’s Louisville, Lexington, Indianapolis, Evansville, Frankfort, and Jeffersonville offices listed. The message carried the confidentiality notice typical of the firm.

Prior to that, on June 9, 2025, at 10:51 AM, Lesly Torres, a paralegal, sent a message to Bryce Koon and cc’d Zachary Reichle, Dennis Cantrell, and Janet Weile regarding the same case. Torres attached copies of discovery requests served that day, in both Word and PDF formats, and enumerated six items:

1) Defendant Naomi Robinson's First Request for Production of Documents to Plaintiff Ashlee Williams;
2) Defendant Naomi Robinson's First Set of Interrogatories to Plaintiff Ashlee Williams;
3) Defendant Naomi Robinson's First Request for Production of Documents to Plaintiff Julmonzhae Moore;
4) Defendant Naomi Robinson's First Set of Interrogatories to Plaintiff Julmonzhae Moore;
5) Defendant Naomi Robinson's First Request for Production of Documents to Plaintiff Dewayne Ward;
6) Defendant Naomi Robinson's First Set of Interrogatories to Plaintiff Dewayne Ward.

Torres closed the message with an offer to address any questions and provided her direct line as 317.61.4224, noting the City as Indianapolis. The cc line listed Zachary Reichle, Dennis Cantrell (Dennis.Cantrell@skofirm.com), and Janet Weile.

In sum, the record reflects a discovery dispute/production timeline in Willaims, Ward & Moore v. Robinson, involving the Plaintiffs Ashlee Williams, Julmonzhae Moore, and Dewayne Ward (the client in this case), with discovery requests served by Naomi Robinson’s team on June 9, 2025; thereafter, communications on July 15 and July 28, 2025 regarding status and the production of discovery materials, including a Dropbox-hosted document production.
